'''Nikolas Kirrill Gvosdev''' (born 11 September 1969<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rivoters.com/mobile/by_number/210011/33435_nikolas_k_gvosdev.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-07-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713165703/http://rivoters.com/mobile/by_number/210011/33435_nikolas_k_gvosdev.html |archive-date=2018-07-13 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>) is a [[Russia]]n-[[United States|American]] international relations scholar. He is currently professor of [[national security]] studies at the U.S. [[Naval War College]] and the former [[Editing|Editor]] of the bi-monthly [[foreign policy]] journal, ''[[The National Interest]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnwc.edu/nikolasgvosdev|title=U.S. Naval War College {{!}} Nikolas K. Gvosdev, Ph.D.|website=www.usnwc.edu|access-date=2016-12-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203234817/https://www.usnwc.edu/NikolasGvosdev|archive-date=2015-02-03|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> He writes widely as a specialist on [[US foreign policy]] as well as international [[politics]] as they affect [[Russia]] and its neighbors.
== Biography == Gvosdev received his [[Doctor of Philosophy|D.Phil.]] as a [[Rhodes Scholar]] at [[St Antony's College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fpri.org/contributor/nikolas-gvosdev-2/|title=Nikolas K. Gvosdev - Foreign Policy Research Institute|publisher=}}</ref>
He worked [[executive editor]] and the [[founding editor]] of ''[[The National Interest]]''. In 2005 he appointed journal's now-defunct separate web edition, In The National Interest. Upon leaving the editorship in 2008, he was succeeded by [[Justine Rosenthal]];<ref>{{cite web |title='The National Interest' Appoints Justine Rosenthal as New Czar |url=http://www.thewashingtonnote.com/archives/2008/05/the_national_in/ |accessdate=January 17, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619071032/http://www.thewashingtonnote.com/archives/2008/05/the_national_in/ |archivedate=June 19, 2009 }}</ref> he remains associated with the journal as a contributing editor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalinterest.org/|title=The National Interest|website=The National Interest}}</ref> He wrote many articles, essays, books. He has appeared as an analyst and a commentator on television and radio likes [[CNN]], [[Fox News]], [[MSNBC]], [[National Public Radio]], [[BBC]], [[C-SPAN]]'s Washington Journal, [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] and [[Voice of America]] <ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.usnwc.edu/NikolasGvosdev |title= U.S Naval War College;Faculty;Profile |access-date= 2015-02-03 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150203234817/https://www.usnwc.edu/NikolasGvosdev |archive-date= 2015-02-03 |dead-url= yes |df= }}</ref>
Gvosdev lived in [[Washington DC]] and served as Senior Fellow for strategic studies at the [[Nixon Center]], and as an Adjunct Professor at [[Georgetown University]] and [[George Washington University]] until 2007. In 2008 he moved to [[Newport, Rhode Island]] and started teaching at the [[Naval War College]]. He is married with one son.
Along with [[Dimitri K. Simes]], [[Anatol Lieven]], and [[John Hulsman]], Gvosdev is seen as one of the proponents of the "new realism" in foreign policy—one that acknowledges a greater role for values than traditional [[realpolitik]] as espoused by [[Henry Kissinger]] but nonetheless puts a stress on setting priorities. He has also been one of the strongest proponents for engagement with Russia and has tended to view [[Vladimir Putin]]'s government in a more positive light than most American commentators, characterizing his regime as "managed pluralism" rather than as an outright authoritarian state. Along with [[Ray Takeyh]], he was an early skeptic of the proposition that the [[Democracy promotion|spread of democracy]] in the Middle East would bring pro-American governments to power.
== Books == * Imperial policies and perspectives towards Georgia, 1760-1819 (St. Martin's Press in association with St. Antony's College, Oxford, 2000) * Emperors and elections : reconciling the Orthodox tradition with modern politics (Huntington, N.Y. : Troitsa Books, 2000) * An examination of church-state relations in the Byzantine and Russian empires with an emphasis on ideology and models of interaction (Lewiston, N.Y.: E. Mellen Press, 2001) * The Receding Shadow of the Prophet: The Rise and Fall of Political Islam (Praeger, 2004) * Russian Foreign Policy: Interests, Vectors and Sectors (CQ Press, 2013, with Christopher Marsh) * US Foreign Policy and Defense Strategy (Georgetown University Press, 2014, with Derek Reveron and Mackubin Owens); * Communitarian Foreign Policy: Amitai Etzioni's Vision (Transaction Publishers, 2015) * US foreign policy and defense strategy: the evolution of an incidental superpower (Georgetown University Press, 2015; with Derek S. Reveron and Mackubin Thomas Owens) * The Oxford handbook of U.S. national security (Oxford University Press, 2018; with Derek S. Reveron; John A. Cloud)
